This is the 3rd time I've attempted to write this review so it should be clear how much i enjoyed my experience & food at Zudar's. Clean & spacious at 1st glance. As I was dining by myself, I found a spot at the bar. I was quickly greeted by Kaley with a smile & menu. I asked about the draft beers available & she even let me try a sample (delicious IPA free dive) Again i asked about a favorite menu item & she guided me towards the Smoked Turkey Special sandwich (delicious & enough to take half my sandwich for a treat later) The menu has so many choices of breads, meats, cheeses, salads & side dishes, vegan & keto options, homemade soups & desserts... It's the comfort food & environment I truly needed that day . My father has had an extended stay at Tampa General with lots of bad news & sad moments. After a long walk to escape such a sad & cold environment (the hospital temperature--all the nurses & staff are expectional & warm) I thought I would pop into publix for a sub (ZUDAR'S is located directly behind publix) I happily discovered this locals & hospital staff favorite casual spot. Please stop in & try this family run  restaurant with great tasting food for a reasonable price. Zudars has heart ❤ and to me, that is priceless. Thank you to Kaley & I wish you all the best in your future & to the owner who took his time to come by & make my experience one I'll never forget

Ordered from uber eats and didnt receive our sides. Food isnt bad  just not outstanding as other breakfast places in the area.
Service was slow and wait staff seemed annoyed and fake. Heard our server talk trash at the counter about my grandfather. She sat at the register and barely looked up from her phone.

I usually get good food when I eat at this location. I stopped going to this location last year because the food started tasting different. I figured I would give them another try. I started eating again at this location for a couple of weeks and noticed that the dining room is empty during lunch time. After eating lunch at this location for the past couple of days, I can understand why there are no customers. I ordered a simple hamburger. the burger came out raw. I asked them to cook another one. The burger came out completely burned. I will not be ordering anything from this place again.

So when you walk in you have no idea what's going on. If you don't see a staff member and first time you will never know to just sit anywhere as there are no signs. Took a seat near the windows and the first person that came by to take our drink order apparently never did. The next guy did and we waited and waited and waited and waited. Never told of specials or the fact can get a flight of mimosas or flavors because they don't tell you. While I write this two people also walked out because they never got greeted or waited on. Finally took pur order and well who knows as still dont even have silverware. The ladies next to us had to ask. Extremely unorganized and lackadaisical. Even if and when we get our food this place is not worth it. Not even busy maybe 6 tables with people and 80% of place empty and now I know why. Bloody Mary is more like colored water and mimosa is actually not bad but love to have known can get a flight for cost of two mimosas. Also other tables if party is of large will be helped before a smaller one in everyway. Worst service ever !  Long story short waiting in here for drinks, food and even help is longer then waiting in a line somewhere else. DO NOT COME HERE FOR BRUNCH OR ANYTHING ELSE !!!
A good neighborhood joint to hang at and have breakfast.
I very much enjoy the staff, friendly without being intrusive...very warm and welcoming! The food is fresh and so yummy! Dinner or lunch, you can't go wrong.
Spa for lunch. Features unique sandwiches, soups, and salad
Absolutely Loved.. The Popeye sandwich.. spinach, tomatoes, provolone, mushrooms, Caesar dressing on pumpernickel.. truly delicious

caption: Fantastic- just ate there for the first time June 24, 2016 service was awesome clean atmosphere I had quiche potatoes and fresh fruit- fabulous 👍🏻👍🏻👍🏻

This was the third time we've tried and its gotten progressively worse each time.   The first time was pretty good.    big chip in the beer glass I was served with an indifferent response when I told them about it ( could have caused nasty cut).   No silverware,  food was not prepared as stated in menu... quesadilla had no cheese and sour cream.... service was slow.. and overall food quality was mediocre and overpriced.  There's better options out there in a very competitive south tampa market.   To add insult,  the owner was at the bar and oblivious to the disaster around him.

My 17 month old son and I stumbled across this place while exploring Tampa.  The hostess/waitress was friendly and helped us find a quiet table in the back.  She also filled my son's bottle with whole milk, brought him a specially made bowl of berries (his favorite) and a big pancake with syrup.  I ordered the The big BLT on Cuban bread which was amazing.  Great place, great food, and they were super attentive to my son.

Love this place! A staple South Tampa restaurant. They now have a bar and patio seating.  My husband gets the Meltdown every time we go. I usually order a Cobb salad and then take the leftovers home for dinner (its that big!).
The new full liquor bar is great. Ordered a chicken caprese sandwich that was very good. I've had soup here in the past and it's always been excellent.

Giving it one star only because I was not given the option to give a negative rating. Made a take out order online and ended up getting the worst service I have ever received. When I arrived to pick up the order,  20 minutes passed before any of the employees even acknowledged us. 8 of us waited at the counter  without a single greeting. At least 5 different employees walked past us without a word. They looked our way but, and I quote, "that was not their job." When someone finally had the decency to attend us, they had no idea where our orders were. They were quick to charge us but then we had to wait another 20 minutes to get the food. At this point my entire lunch break had passed. Oh and let me add that the wait was endured through a temporature of 90 degrees because their AC seemed to be broken. Its a shame that they have such imcompetent members on their staff because honestly the food isnt half bad.  It just isnt good enough for me to ever go back.

Ordered 2 sandwiches 2 glasses of tea for $24.50. The sandwiches were poor quality not good I brought this issue to the waiter with no response. I use to visit this place on a regular basis a couple of years ago. Maybe something happened new ownership etc. Will not recommend again.....
Slow service when crowded although courteous. Good desserts, ordinary main dishes and sandwiches. I live nearby but not worth the short trip.

It would be nice if this place was actually open during the hours they claim.  I went there around 6-6:15pm ON A FRIDAY, and they were not open.  Also at lunchtime during the week (12:30-1pm) they were not open.  Hmmm.  Makes me wonder.  Maybe a front for something else?

Bacon brownies. The sign had intrigued me and mocked me for two years and every time I went to Publix to do some light grocery shopping. No. I don’t cook. You already know that. But I craft and serve incredible alcoholic libations. Isn’t a Bloody Mary a meal on its own? Couldn’t a cucumber gimlet adorned with basil and a sliced cucumber act as a liquid salad? If I only drink those… am I juicing? The sign bothered me. The deli says absolutely nothing in that corner. It is not ugly enough or pretty enough… it is just blah and there. Since I am observing the strictly-no-eating –out-a-lot counsel of my irrational accountant post tax day, I had to grocery shop. He had also advised me to never go grocery shopping while I am hungry. What is a girl to do? I was starving as I held my ecologically caring reusable grocery bags. As my platform heel stepped out of Aurora (Yes, I named my car), a Shakespearean existential question was asked: To eat or not to eat… To eat. Imagine all the money I was saving by not going into Publix famished and depressed. I would have paid for cases of twinkies. I would have bought and carried out ho-ho’s (no pun intended. My friends were not with me). I might have kidnapped Sara Lee, Aunt Jemima and Ben and Jerry. No bueno! I casually crossed the street and entered Zudar’s. The insignificant outside is misleading. The place was packed. There was one table of two left untouched and ready for me right at the front door. Was this the deli version of Ciro’s Speakeasy? It was two o’clock and the place was a convention center for the hungry businessmen. Servers were running around taking orders, delivering food, answering phones and handing out bills. I tried to coyly reach the table in anonymity. It was not to happen. A table of six men (eating half sandwiches and a side of salad) turned and smiled. Up and down and up and down their eyes went. Had they confused me with Angelina Jolie? Maybe. I was having a really good hair day. I might have been pouting even. I knew the fascination with me would end the minute I ordered my food. The green-eyed foodie was with me so we ordered a mixed Reuben (corned beef hash and roast beef), a chicken parmesan sandwich, a side order of mac and cheese (because one can never have tried it enough. I want to be like a barista of the stuff. A macancheeserista.) We had promised to try the bacon brownies somehow too. Even when Zudar’s was filled with costumers, the service pulled through. Those tables were turning fast. Within ten minutes we were eating our sandwiches and harassing one another picking out food from the other’s plate. Great sandwiches. Huge. Wonderful value. The mac and cheese proved to be a slightly better version of the powdered Kraft one. Even the macaroni itself was a twin brother of the Kraft kind. Disillusioned. I asked for the brownies to go. It turned out that there was also one kind made with peanut butter and bacon. So we did order enough to sample them. I can’t say if the experience of them while in the deli would have been any different. They were given to me individually wrapped in plastic wrap and they seemed cold and fudgey rather than brownish. Dense is an understatement. One tiny corner and the explosion of flavors left you baffled. The chocolate dissolves and you are left with serious bits of bacon and bacon fat slathered on the roof of your mouth. I believe these brownies are like one of those love or hate relationships. No matter how you look at them, when it is over you are bound to have a memorable aftertaste.

We were visiting Tampa for the first time for a conference and mini vacation. We make a point to support the local resturant scene wherever we are. Zubar's exceded our expectations! We enjoyed our visit to Zubar's more than any other meal. Great food and service.
Our family eats here regularly.  Menu has a ton of variety for adults and kids, and everything we have tried has been great.  Soup specials change pretty often, some of them are quite unique.

I work in south Tampa, and I've been to Zudar's three times for lunch.  I've had their Reuben, Cuban, and the "Key West Sampler" basket -- fried shrimp, fish nuggets and a crab cake.  Today I took my wife there for lunch and she raved about her burger.  I think I've found another "go to" place for a quick lunch.  Service is friendly, food is tasty, ingredients seem to be high quality, and I leave full.  The price is what I'd expect in south Tampa.
this was a great find; was a surprise last minute stop. I was impressed.
we got robbed by these bastards.......we hauled 3 1/2 tons of concrete and never got paid at this joint........us poor bastards had to haul their sht for free......gd it.
The Best Desserts! But I'm not that impressed in their dishes. Good service and cool decor, love it!

Just finished eating a cuban sandwich from there. The quality of the meat and the serving size are both poor. The pork patty tasted like a bland piece of chewy rubber from a microwave. On top of that, you're paying twice as much half the serving of anywhere else I've been. You'll get a much better sandwich from a grocery store deli or even the premades at a gas station.
